// The wired-in `prelude` module. Every operator desugars to one of these functions, and the module
// is default-imported into every user module (so `prelude.add` and stdlib submodules resolve).
//
// Generic bounds give operators precise typing: an arithmetic operator over `T extends number`
// preserves `integer` when both operands are integers, and widens to `number` otherwise.

// Arithmetic -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@"Add two numbers; preserves integer when both operands are integers."
primitive agent add[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> T
@"Subtract two numbers; preserves integer when both operands are integers."
primitive agent subtract[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> T
@"Multiply two numbers; preserves integer when both operands are integers."
primitive agent multiply[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> T
@"Floor-modulo two numbers; preserves integer when both operands are integers. A zero divisor
panics (guard with a comparison first)."
primitive agent modulo[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> T
@"Divide two numbers; always yields a number. A zero divisor panics (guard with a comparison
first) — division never yields Infinity / NaN."
primitive agent divide(left: number, right: number) -> number
@"Negate a number; preserves integer."
primitive agent negate[T extends number](value: T) -> T

// Comparison -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@"Whether two values are equal."
primitive agent equal[T](left: T, right: T) -> boolean
@"Whether two values are not equal."
primitive agent not_equal[T](left: T, right: T) -> boolean
@"Whether the left number is less than the right."
primitive agent less_than[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> boolean
@"Whether the left number is less than or equal to the right."
primitive agent less_or_equal[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> boolean
@"Whether the left number is greater than the right."
primitive agent greater_than[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> boolean
@"Whether the left number is greater than or equal to the right."
primitive agent greater_or_equal[T extends number](left: T, right: T) -> boolean

// Logical ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@"Logical conjunction."
primitive agent and(left: boolean, right: boolean) -> boolean
@"Logical disjunction."
primitive agent or(left: boolean, right: boolean) -> boolean
@"Logical negation."
primitive agent not(value: boolean) -> boolean

// String -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@"Concatenate two strings."
primitive agent concat(left: string, right: string) -> string

// Errors -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
//
// The two error channels:
//
//   - `throw[T]` (below) is the error channel for programs: anticipated, domain-specific failures a
//     caller may recover from. The payload type is an error `data` declared next to the operation
//     that fails (`json.parse_error`, `http.fetch_error`, ...). Raises in one scope join to the
//     payload union (`throw[a] | throw[b]` is `throw[a | b]`), and a handler discharges exactly the
//     payload its parameter annotation names — handle the whole union, or rethrow the rest.
//
//   - `panic` is the runtime's own failure signal and has no declaration here on purpose: a program
//     can neither raise it nor handle it. The runtime panics on invariant violations (a
//     non-exhaustive match, a zero divisor, an FFI infrastructure error, an engine backstop), and an
//     unhandled panic fails the run. Recovery from a broken invariant is not a program-level
//     concern; re-running is.

@"Signal a typed error the caller may recover from. The payload is a domain-specific error `data`
(e.g. `json.parse_error`); a handler at that payload type catches it — `use handler { request
throw(error: my_error) -> never { break fallback } }` — and an unhandled throw fails the run with
the payload. `-> never` means a throw cannot be resumed: a handler recovers by `break`ing out of
the handle (or rethrows)."
request throw[T](error: T) -> never
